The current issue I am running into: how do I get a process to wait and/or restart once the mediator has data? I&#39;ve got it making a call to the function inside the mediator but that recalls the constructor which isn&#39;t ideal (example below):

      const staff = mediator.sendRequest(&#39;staff&#39;, process.argv[2]); 
      // calls the constructor of mediator due to being a new process

      if (!staff) {
        return; // exits out the function
      }

So I&#39;m thinking of using process.send() to request the data before returning out incomplete. The caveat of this is that the process then relies on being a forked process instead of being on its own. 

        process.send({
          status: &#39;Waiting for staff to be populated.&#39;,
          requestFor: &#39;staff&#39;,
        });
This also poses the problem of how I start the process once the data has been received. As you can see above, I post the name of the process in `process.argv[2]` which enables it to be recalled as a child process, which is fine but then I would need to pass through the data as a message.

